<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Stephen Rickitt – Written evidence</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Stephen </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Rickitt</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – Written evidence</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">THE DRAFT DEREGULATION BILL</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">SUBMISSION FOR AMENDMENTS TO CLAUSE 16 (AMENDMENTS TO SECTION 147 HIGHWAYS ACT 1980)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">SUBMISSION FOR THE INCLUSION OF AMENDMENTS TO THE EXISTING PROVISIONS FOR THE INSTALLATION OF CATTLE GRIDS (SECTIONS 82-89 AND SCHEDULE 10 HIGHWAYS ACT 1980</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Part 1 – Clause 16</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Suggested Further Amendment Number One</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This section applies to all highways other than a classified road or a special road.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">1. The inclusion of restricted byways and byways open to all traffic is welcomed.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2. There are minor roads which are neither type of byway but which have, or could usefully have,</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> gates for the same purposes.</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:dotted; border-bottom-width:3pt; clear:both; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">3. The exclusions are based on section 116 Highways Act 1980</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Suggested Further Amendment Number Two</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The words</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> “for enabling the footpath or bridleway to be used” are</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> added to subsection (2).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">4. In Kind</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> v Northumberland County Council [2012] EWHC 603 (Admin) at </span><a href="http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2012/603.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2012/603.html</span></a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">at</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> paragraph 17 the Court suggested additional wording for section 147 (my emphasis):</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="para17"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">17. Although I have some sympathy for the argument that a broader approach should be taken to the interpretation of section 147(2), I am unable to accept it. Section 147(1) refers to a "footpath or bridleway that crosses the land", an expression that is apt to refer to the whole line of the route. By contrast section 147(2) refers to the exercise of "the right of way", an expression which naturally directs attention to the nature of that right. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">If in section 147(2) Parliament had intended to refer to the path or bridleway as a whole, I have little doubt that it would have used the expression "for enabling the footpath or bridleway to be used", or some similar words</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. Moreover, I am </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">unable to accept Miss </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Stockley’s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> submission that the appellant’s interpretation of section 147 is unworkable in practice. What constitutes "undue inconvenience to the public" will vary from case to case, depending, no doubt on the nature and location of the footpath or bridleway in question. Each case has to be considered on its own facts and the highway authority must make its own judgment when deciding what conditions to impose. </span></a></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:dotted; border-bottom-width:3pt; clear:both; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">5. Adoption of this phrase would provide greater flexibility for landowners, famers and highway authorities without practically detracting from the rights of the public to use a public highway.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Suggested Further Amendment Number Three</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A further subsection is added to section 147</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing, a highway authority may grant consent under this section for the installation of a cattle grid across the entire width of a highway on the condition that a bypass is provided at all times and for the purpose of this section “bypass” shall have the same meaning as in section 82(6) [of the Highways Act 1980].</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">6. The issue in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Kind v Northumberland (above) </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">related to the provision of a cattle grid across a three metre wide public bridleway. The bridleway was along a straight farm access at that point. The highway authority allowed the cattle grid on condition that a bypass was provided. The Court found against the highway authority.</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:dotted; border-bottom-width:3pt; clear:both; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">7. This provision would allow greater common sense to be used by highway authorities when balancing the interests of farmers and the highway users.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Part 2 – New provisions</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Suggested Further Provision</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In sections 82-89 and Schedule 10 [Highways Act 1980] references to ministerial approval are deleted</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">8. Sections 82-89 and Schedule 10 Highways Act 1980 provide an elaborate system for authorising the installation of cattle grids.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">9. The provisions are derived from the Highways (Provision of Cattle Grids) Act 1950. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Hansard</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> makes it clear </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> cattle grids were a new phenomenon at that time.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">10. In my experience, highway officers and landowners/farmers were put off from replacing gates with cattle grids because of the cost of the procedure.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">11. Is there now any need for ministerial consent? I suggest that cattle grids should be treated in the same way as other installations within the highway and left to the local highway authority. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">11 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">From 1989 to 2012, I was a lawyer working for Northumberland County Council on highway, rights of way and other issues.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This note represents my own views and does not necessarily represent the views of the County Council.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Copies:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Dave Waterman – DEFRA</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Helen Lancaster and David Brookes – Northumberland County Council</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>